but following a drivers' meeting,

6
00:01:05,332 --> 00:01:07,233
a decision has finally been taken.

7
00:01:07,234 --> 00:01:08,415
Three minutes to go.

8
00:01:09,092 --> 00:01:11,174
Everybody off the grid now.

9
00:01:25,172 --> 00:01:29,257
Twenty-five drivers start
every season in Formula 1,

10
00:01:29,332 --> 00:01:32,415
and each year two of us die.

11
00:01:33,172 --> 00:01:35,539
What kind of person
does a job like this?

12
00:01:36,692 --> 00:01:38,694
Not normal men, for sure.

13
00:01:38,772 --> 00:01:43,016
Rebels, lunatics, dreamers.

14
00:01:43,692 --> 00:01:46,093
People who are desperate
to make a mark

15
00:01:46,212 --> 00:01:48,453
and are prepared to die trying.

16
00:01:50,532 --> 00:01:51,897
My name is Niki Lauda,

17
00:01:52,252 --> 00:01:55,381
and racing people know
me for two things.

18
00:01:55,452 --> 00:01:59,218
The first is my rivalry with him.

19
00:02:01,570 --> 00:02:03,110
You want to change?

20
00:02:03,372 --> 00:02:06,296
Photographers, please
clear the grid.

21
00:02:06,812 --> 00:02:08,780
What about Hunt? Has he changed?

22
00:02:09,052 --> 00:02:10,497
No, he's going on wets.

23
00:02:10,572 --> 00:02:13,735
I don't know why it
became such a big thing.

24
00:02:13,772 --> 00:02:17,140
We were just drivers busting
each other's balls.

25
00:02:18,132 --> 00:02:20,578
To me this is perfectly normal,

26
00:02:20,652 --> 00:02:22,814
but other people saw
it differently,

27
00:02:22,892 --> 00:02:25,816
that whatever it was
between us went deeper.

28
00:02:27,350 --> 00:02:30,270
Then we go on wets too.

29
00:02:42,092 --> 00:02:44,094
The other thing I'm remembered for

30
00:02:44,172 --> 00:02:47,938
is what happened on
1st August, 1976,

31
00:02:48,012 --> 00:02:51,694
when I was chasing
him like an asshole.

32
00:03:22,212 --> 00:03:23,657
Trauma trolley, please.

33
00:03:23,732 --> 00:03:24,818
Hello, I think the racetrack

34
00:03:24,819 --> 00:03:26,252
telephoned ahead
that I was coming.

35
00:03:26,272 --> 00:03:27,717
Hunt. James Hunt.

36
00:03:32,732 --> 00:03:35,815
What's the matter? No one ever
seen a spot of blood before?

37
00:03:36,172 --> 00:03:38,823
- Are you all right?
- Absolutely fine.

38
00:03:41,972 --> 00:03:43,861
We all thought you'd
been in an accident.

39
00:03:43,972 --> 00:03:45,019
I have.

40
00:03:45,172 --> 00:03:46,822
If you call a
friendly disagreement

41
00:03:46,823 --> 00:03:48,335
with another driver an accident.

42
00:03:54,492 --> 00:03:56,256
What did you disagree about?

43
00:03:56,332 --> 00:03:57,902
It's none of your business.

44
00:03:58,012 --> 00:04:00,014
Sorry.

45
00:04:01,012 --> 00:04:02,377
His wife.

46
00:04:04,412 --> 00:04:06,938
That's going to need a couple
of stitches. It's a nasty cut.

47
00:04:07,012 --> 00:04:10,095
It was a nasty blow. Done
with a bloody crowbar.

48
00:04:11,012 --> 00:04:13,777
- Why? What did you do?
- Nothing.

49
00:04:14,372 --> 00:04:16,613
Only what she asked me to do.

50
00:04:18,852 --> 00:04:20,377
Which was...

51
00:04:21,012 --> 00:04:23,538
I'd be happy to show
you, if you like.

52
00:04:26,732 --> 00:04:29,019
Oh. Sorry.

53
00:04:29,132 --> 00:04:32,932
I have a theory why women
like racing drivers.

54
00:04:33,292 --> 00:04:35,613
It's not because they
respect what we do,

55
00:04:35,692 --> 00:04:38,502
driving round and
round in circles.

56
00:04:38,572 --> 00:04:41,143
Mostly they think that's pathetic,
and they're probably right.

57
00:04:42,372 --> 00:04:44,454
It's our closeness to death.

58
00:04:45,292 --> 00:04:48,978
You see, the closer you are to
death, the more alive you feel.

59
00:04:49,052 --> 00:04:52,056
The more alive you are. And
they can see that in you.

60
00:04:52,132 --> 00:04:54,055
They feel that in you.

61
00:04:55,212 --> 00:04:57,453
My name is James Hunt.

62
00:04:57,572 --> 00:04:59,574
My father is a stockbroker,

63
00:04:59,612 --> 00:05:03,219
my sister is a barrister and
my brother is an accountant.

64
00:05:04,292 --> 00:05:05,737
And I...

65
00:05:06,252 --> 00:05:07,902
Well, I do this.

66
00:05:09,412 --> 00:05:10,937
It's a wonderful way to live.

67
00:05:11,092 --> 00:05:13,140
It's the only way to drive.

68
00:05:14,092 --> 00:05:16,493
As if each day is your last.

69
00:05:25,772 --> 00:05:28,252
I've never been to a
Grand Prix before.

70
00:05:28,332 --> 00:05:30,175
Oh, you still haven't.

71
00:05:30,252 --> 00:05:32,778
- This is Formula 3.
- What's that?

72
00:05:33,612 --> 00:05:35,853
It's a lower division,

73
00:05:35,932 --> 00:05:38,458
where idiots like me mess about

74
00:05:38,852 --> 00:05:40,519
in the hope of being
talent-spotted

75
00:05:40,520 --> 00:05:41,537
to race in Formula 1.

76
00:05:41,612 --> 00:05:43,614
- You look disappointed.
- No.

77
00:05:44,092 --> 00:05:47,301
Ah. You only slept with me because
you thought I was famous.

78
00:05:47,372 --> 00:05:48,942
That's not true.

79
00:05:49,612 --> 00:05:51,614
Don't worry. I will be one day.

80
00:05:51,692 --> 00:05:53,296
Morning, everyone.

81
00:05:53,332 --> 00:05:54,936
- This is Nursie.
- Gemma.

82
00:05:55,612 --> 00:05:58,456
Nursie, this is Bubbles
Horsley, team manager.

83
00:05:58,532 --> 00:05:59,613
How do you do?

84
00:06:00,012 --> 00:06:01,776
- Bubbles?
- Yeah.

85
00:06:01,812 --> 00:06:04,816
- Doc Postlethwaite, our designer.
- How do you do?

86
00:06:04,892 --> 00:06:08,817
And Alexander, Lord
Hesketh, the team's owner.

87
00:06:09,852 --> 00:06:11,342
How do you do?

88
00:06:12,172 --> 00:06:13,662
Fine, thanks.

89
00:06:13,692 --> 00:06:15,581
Well done, Superstar.

90
00:06:15,652 --> 00:06:18,178
- That's the car?
- Yep, that's her.

91
00:06:18,292 --> 00:06:20,021
Lotus 59.

92
00:06:20,132 --> 00:06:22,863
1,000cc Cosworth MAE engine.

93
00:06:22,972 --> 00:06:25,816
She's no beauty, but
goes like the clappers.

94
00:06:32,372 --> 00:06:34,532
Nothing to be worried about.
Does it before every race.

95
00:06:34,552 --> 00:06:36,574
Good sign, actually.
Means he's stoked.

96
00:06:36,652 --> 00:06:40,862
AH Formula 3 cars to the
assembly area now, please.

97
00:06:52,572 --> 00:06:55,781
Drivers please bring them to
the scrutineering bay now.

98
00:06:56,172 --> 00:06:57,742
All right, Superstar?

99
00:06:57,852 --> 00:06:59,536
Never better, patron.

100
00:06:59,572 --> 00:07:02,052
- Have a gargle with this.
- Thank you.

101
00:07:03,532 --> 00:07:04,943
Quick toke of this.

102
00:07:05,852 --> 00:07:08,742
At Crystal Palace today,
James Hunt's on pole,

103
00:07:09,572 --> 00:07:12,860
with Austrian newcomer
Niki Lauda alongside him

104
00:07:12,892 --> 00:07:15,543
and Dave Walker completing Row 1.

105
00:07:15,612 --> 00:07:18,092
Row 2 is Mike Beuttler
and Dave Morgan,

106
00:07:18,212 --> 00:07:20,339
with Tony Trimmer
and Gerry Birrell.

107
00:07:20,340 --> 00:07:21,340
Who's that?

108
00:07:21,452 --> 00:07:22,977
He's new.

109
00:07:23,452 --> 00:07:26,296
- Some German.
- Austrian.

110
00:07:26,372 --> 00:07:29,455
He's been here since 5:00
am, walking the track.

111
00:07:29,532 --> 00:07:31,899
You might actually have to
concentrate today, James.

112
00:07:31,972 --> 00:07:33,576
You'll need these.

113
00:07:34,252 --> 00:07:36,823
Okay, start her up.

114
00:07:36,892 --> 00:07:39,372
Ah. What music.

115
00:07:39,412 --> 00:07:40,902
They could never have imagined it,

116
00:07:40,972 --> 00:07:43,259
those pioneers who
invented the automobile,

117
00:07:43,372 --> 00:07:45,477
that it would possess
us like this,

118
00:07:45,478 --> 00:07:47,582
in our imaginations,
in our dreams.

119
00:07:48,332 --> 00:07:50,619
Nursie, men love women,

120
00:07:50,732 --> 00:07:52,496
but even more than that,

121
00:07:52,572 --> 00:07:55,894
men love cars.

122
00:08:03,012 --> 00:08:06,175
- Come on, James.
- James. Come on, James.

123
00:08:07,172 --> 00:08:08,583
Go, James.

124
00:08:16,252 --> 00:08:17,413
Hunt's still in the lead,

125
00:08:17,492 --> 00:08:19,654
but Niki Lauda is
right on his tail.

126
00:08:28,452 --> 00:08:31,296
Hunt and Lauda are proving to
be in a class of their own.

127
00:08:31,332 --> 00:08:32,936
They're leaving the
pack far behind.

128
00:08:33,332 --> 00:08:34,936
Herr Red Devil's on his tail.

129
00:08:41,052 --> 00:08:43,054
Lauda takes a look
down the inside...

130
00:08:44,692 --> 00:08:46,456
and he's sold him a dummy.

131
00:08:49,972 --> 00:08:51,974
Lauda is through.
He's in the lead.

132
00:08:52,812 --> 00:08:55,213
Hunt will be determined to
make up for that mistake.

133
00:09:01,972 --> 00:09:03,542
Hunt's in Lauda's slipstream.

134
00:09:03,652 --> 00:09:05,620
Lauda's not leaving any gap.

135
00:09:10,732 --> 00:09:14,737
The Lotus goes for the inside.
It's an aggressive move from Hunt.

136
00:09:18,812 --> 00:09:20,735
Oh. There's contact.

137
00:09:27,492 --> 00:09:30,735
The leaders have spun out.
Lauda's facing the wrong way.

138
00:09:31,332 --> 00:09:33,699
The back marker's gone through.

139
00:09:34,052 --> 00:09:35,656
You can see why
Hunt's fellow drivers

140
00:09:35,732 --> 00:09:37,573
call him Hunt the Shunt.

141
00:09:41,012 --> 00:09:42,013
Asshole.

142
00:09:42,092 --> 00:09:43,856
- Go on, James.
- The Kraut's out of it.

143
00:09:44,172 --> 00:09:46,095
Lauda is clearly furious.

144
00:09:46,172 --> 00:09:49,619
There's every reason to expect
sharp words in the pits.

145
00:09:49,692 --> 00:09:51,581
It's gonna be victory for Hunt.

146
00:09:51,692 --> 00:09:55,014
It's gonna be an ignominious
defeat for Niki Lauda.

147
00:09:59,732 --> 00:10:03,623
So James Hunt scores his third
major Formula 3 win of the season

148
00:10:03,692 --> 00:10:04,932
here at Crystal Palace,

149
00:10:05,052 --> 00:10:07,783
after a desperate
battle with Niki Lauda.

150
00:10:07,852 --> 00:10:09,581
Lauda was unable to restart

151
00:10:09,692 --> 00:10:12,423
after Hunt's aggressive move
caused them both to spin out

152
00:10:12,532 --> 00:10:13,693
in the last lap of the race.

153
00:10:15,132 --> 00:10:16,812
Hard luck. Better luck next time.

154
00:10:17,372 --> 00:10:18,897
Hey, asshole.

155
00:10:19,972 --> 00:10:22,134
That was my line. I
had that corner.

156
00:10:22,212 --> 00:10:23,834
Do you mean the one
that you spun out

157
00:10:23,835 --> 00:10:25,455
of and finished
facing the other way?

158
00:10:25,572 --> 00:10:27,893
I think that corner had you.

159
00:10:27,972 --> 00:10:30,498
That move was total suicide.
What if I hadn't braked?

160
00:10:30,572 --> 00:10:33,416
- We'd have crashed.
- But we didn't, did we?

161
00:10:33,452 --> 00:10:35,420
Thanks to your impeccable
survival instincts.

162
00:10:37,572 --> 00:10:39,415
Fuck you. What's your name?

163
00:10:41,052 --> 00:10:45,421
James Simon Wallis Hunt. Remember
it, my little Jerry friend.

164
00:10:45,772 --> 00:10:47,422
Jawohl. Remember ze name.

165
00:10:47,452 --> 00:10:50,262
And it's very simple.
Hunt. It rhymes with...

166
00:10:50,292 --> 00:10:51,418
cunt.

167
00:10:51,492 --> 00:10:53,972
A word that happens to
describe you perfectly.

168
00:10:54,572 --> 00:10:56,017
Who was that?

169
00:10:56,092 --> 00:10:58,254
I've no idea. He looks
like a rat, doesn't he?

170
00:11:00,572 --> 00:11:02,017
In my home town, Vienna,

171
00:11:02,452 --> 00:11:05,774
my family is famous for
one thing, business.

172
00:11:06,332 --> 00:11:08,619
My grandfather was a businessman,

173
00:11:09,092 --> 00:11:10,537
my father, too.

174
00:11:11,332 --> 00:11:14,461
So when they heard I wanted
to race cars for a living,

175
00:11:14,532 --> 00:11:16,341
they had a few things to say.

176
00:11:16,710 --> 00:11:18,380
Never.

177
00:11:18,840 --> 00:11:21,460
Racing is for playboys
and dilettantes.

178
00:11:21,670 --> 00:11:24,260
Frivolous amateurs with
nothing in their heads.

179
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:26,590
The name Lauda...

180
00:11:26,970 --> 00:11:29,600
belongs with politicians
and economists,

181
00:11:30,100 --> 00:11:31,600
on the front pages.

182
00:11:32,060 --> 00:11:34,100
What if this is all I can do?

183
00:11:34,390 --> 00:11:37,190
Then you need my money
more than ever,

184
00:11:37,650 --> 00:11:40,480
so do as I say and follow me
into the family business.

185
00:11:41,452 --> 00:11:42,817
Gut.

186
00:11:46,530 --> 00:11:48,410
Keep your money.

187
00:11:48,740 --> 00:11:50,700
Don't invest in me.

188
00:11:51,040 --> 00:11:53,330
But when I'm world champion

189
00:11:53,700 --> 00:11:56,370
and my name is on the
front pages too...

190
00:11:56,710 --> 00:11:58,460
you will regret it.

191
00:11:59,540 --> 00:12:02,590
Get out and never
show your face again.

192
00:12:03,492 --> 00:12:05,494
So if my family wasn't
going to help me,

193
00:12:05,652 --> 00:12:09,338
I decided to risk everything
and take out a loan myself.

194
00:12:09,412 --> 00:12:12,382
I found a Formula 1
team with an okay car

195
00:12:12,492 --> 00:12:14,540
and an owner who had
run out of money

196
00:12:14,652 --> 00:12:16,814
and was willing to
accept my terms.

197
00:12:17,212 --> 00:12:18,896
And so, ladies and gentlemen,

198
00:12:19,012 --> 00:12:20,776
I'm delighted to say

199
00:12:20,852 --> 00:12:22,730
that the winner of the
Guild of Motoring

200
00:12:22,731 --> 00:12:24,379
Writers Award Driver
of the Year...

201
00:12:25,572 --> 00:12:27,073
is James Hunt.

202
00:12:30,492 --> 00:12:31,937
Superb news.

203
00:12:32,692 --> 00:12:34,854
- Well done, James.
- Superstar.

204
00:12:35,012 --> 00:12:36,457
Fantastic.

205
00:12:38,012 --> 00:12:40,219
- Well done. Congratulations.
- Thank you so much.

206
00:12:40,372 --> 00:12:41,453
Yes.

207
00:12:41,532 --> 00:12:42,863
Erm...

208
00:12:42,892 --> 00:12:45,702
You know, my parents always
wanted me to be a doctor...

209
00:12:45,852 --> 00:12:47,900
or a stockbroker or something.

210
00:12:48,012 --> 00:12:49,696
They gave me the
first-class education,

211
00:12:49,772 --> 00:12:51,854
but, well, that all
went terribly wrong

212
00:12:51,932 --> 00:12:53,972
and I ended up with you lot.

213
00:12:56,772 --> 00:12:58,292
Thank you. I need it
more than you do.

214
00:13:00,412 --> 00:13:04,098
I mean, I have a hot head, an
inability to tolerate discipline.

215
00:13:04,212 --> 00:13:05,577
- Yes.
- Very true.

216
00:13:06,292 --> 00:13:08,135
I fall out with people
left and right.

217
00:13:08,772 --> 00:13:10,363
The only creatures
I've ever really

218
00:13:10,364 --> 00:13:11,821
loved or have treated honourably

219
00:13:11,892 --> 00:13:13,894
are budgerigars.

220
00:13:15,212 --> 00:13:19,217
So in any normal area of life I'd
be... or I am, a total liability.

221
00:13:19,572 --> 00:13:21,892
The only thing I've got going
for me is I'm quick in a car.

222
00:13:22,052 --> 00:13:24,012
So, thank you for this and
for acknowledging that.

223
00:13:24,052 --> 00:13:25,497
I'm going to give it to my father

224
00:13:25,572 --> 00:13:27,336
and tell him to put
it on the mantelpiece

225
00:13:27,412 --> 00:13:29,733
and imagine it's a first-class
degree in medicine.

226
00:13:45,092 --> 00:13:46,935
Well done, Superstar.

227
00:13:46,972 --> 00:13:49,578
Another season like that and I'll
move you up to the big time.

228
00:13:49,692 --> 00:13:51,262
Come on, you don't
think I'm ready now?

229
00:13:51,332 --> 00:13:54,700
You are. I'm not. I've got
to find you a car first.

230
00:13:54,852 --> 00:13:57,173
Well, go on, then. Chop-chop.

231
00:13:57,252 --> 00:13:58,649
Don't wait too long.
You don't want

232
00:13:58,650 --> 00:13:59,852
him to do what Lauda just did.

233
00:13:59,872 --> 00:14:02,616
- Why? What did he do?
- Got himself a drive with BRM.

234
00:14:02,652 --> 00:14:04,859
Well, how the hell did he
do that? He's a nobody.

235
00:14:04,932 --> 00:14:06,377
He's never won a bloody thing.

236
00:14:06,452 --> 00:14:08,375
Apparently, took out a
loan and bought his way in

237
00:14:08,452 --> 00:14:10,102
with two million
Austrian schillings.

238
00:14:10,172 --> 00:14:11,617
Jesus.

239
00:14:31,132 --> 00:14:34,181
Niki Lauda. Here for
pre-season testing. BRM?

240
00:14:35,692 --> 00:14:38,502
Sign the release form. I'll
let them know you're here.

241
00:14:50,252 --> 00:14:51,777
- Mr Stanley.
- Good morning.

242
00:14:51,812 --> 00:14:54,736
- Good morning.
- Good morning. Clay.

243
00:14:54,812 --> 00:14:57,497
Let me introduce you to
our number-one driver,

244
00:14:57,572 --> 00:14:59,574
Clay Regazzoni.

245
00:15:00,972 --> 00:15:02,701
- How are you?
- Good.

246
00:15:03,452 --> 00:15:06,456
- Pleasure.
- And these are your mechanics.

247
00:15:07,012 --> 00:15:11,461
They're reporting exclusively
to you, as per contract.

248
00:15:11,532 --> 00:15:13,296
Pleasure. Do you
wanna see the car?

249
00:15:13,372 --> 00:15:14,817
Sure.

250
00:15:16,852 --> 00:15:18,263
Hello.

251
00:15:23,292 --> 00:15:25,738
There she is. P160.

252
00:15:26,612 --> 00:15:29,138
- Same as Regazzoni's?
- Identical in every detail.

253
00:15:30,092 --> 00:15:31,582
How much does she weigh?

254
00:15:31,732 --> 00:15:34,338
- 600 kilos.
